              <DefinitionShort>to be sick with a fever</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>to have a fever</Gloss>
                <Gloss>fever</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>Though in a number of languages one can say ‘a person has a fever,’ in some languages the reverse expression is used, for example, ‘the fever has a person.’ Similarly, instead of saying ‘a person has a disease,’ it is ‘the disease which grabs a person.’ One may often speak of a fever as ‘to become hot’ or ‘to burn’ or ‘to be sick with burning.’|It is also possible to understand πίμπρημι in {S:04402800600012} as a process of swelling up (see {D:23.163}).</Comments>
